## Why Noma

::tabs
:::tab{title="vs Markdown"}
Markdown is excellent for prose, weak for layout, charts, semantic
blocks, agent collaboration, validation, and book-scale authoring.
Noma keeps Markdown's readability and adds the missing structure.
:::

:::tab{title="vs Raw HTML"}
HTML is excellent as a rendering target, unpleasant as long-term
source. Noisy diffs, fragile under agent edits, awkward for books,
custom validation. Noma keeps HTML as the output and gives you a
clean source.
:::

:::tab{title="The thesis"}
**Noma is readable source for beautiful agent artifacts.**

Markdown is too weak. HTML is too noisy as source. Noma is the
missing middle: plain-text source → typed AST → HTML / PDF / book /
slides / LLM context.
:::
::

## The central design test

::decision{id="design-test" status="accepted"}
Every Noma feature must answer **yes** to all three:

1. Can a human understand this in raw text?
2. Can an agent edit this safely without destroying the document?
3. Can it render into an artifact people actually want to read?
::

> Read this page's `.noma` source side-by-side with the rendered HTML to
> see how little ceremony Noma adds. Every block above is a few lines of
> readable plain text — the styling, layout, and structure come from the
> renderer, not from inline CSS or hand-authored HTML.
